SIMPLE: effigy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Effigy
<hw>Ef"fi*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Effigies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>effigies</ets>,
fr. <ets>effingere</ets> to form, fashion; <ets>ex</ets> +
<ets>fingere</ets> to form, shape, devise. See <er>Feign</er>.]</ety>
<def>The image, likeness, or representation of a person, whether a full
figure, or a part; an imitative figure; -- commonly applied to
sculptured likenesses, as those on monuments, or to those of the heads
of princes on coins and medals, sometimes applied to
portraits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To burn in effigy</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To
hang in effigy</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to burn or to hang an image or
picture of a person, as a token of public odium.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Efflagitate</ent>⟦br⟧
